[[File:1820 map of the Edmonton Hundred.jpg|thumbnail|1820 map of the Edmonton Hundred by [[Christopher Greenwood (cartographer)|Greenwood]] based on the boundaries stated in the [[Doomsday Book]] of 1086.]]
The '''Edmonton Hundred Historical Society''' is a historical society devoted to the study of the area once covered by the [[Edmonton Hundred]] (a [[hundred (county division)|hundred]] being a former division of a county).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160731041903/http://n21.net/edmonton-hundred-historical-society-home-page.html Edmonton Hundred Historical Society page on N21.net], archived from [http://n21.net/edmonton-hundred-historical-society-home-page.html the original] on July 31st 2016.</ref> The society is a registered charity No. 299073.<ref>[http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityWithoutPartB.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=299073&SubsidiaryNumber=0 EDMONTON HUNDRED HISTORICAL SOCIETY.] [[Charity Commission]]. Retrieved 22 September 2015.</ref> [[David Pam]], [[Fellow of the Royal Historical Society|FRHS]], was the president until his death in 2014.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160731041903/http://n21.net/edmonton-hundred-historical-society-home-page.html Edmonton Hundred Historical Society page on N21.net], archived from [http://n21.net/edmonton-hundred-historical-society-home-page.html the original] on July 31st 2016.</ref>

