{{Grammatical categories}} A '''grammeme''' in [[linguistics]] is a unit of [[grammar]], just as a [[lexeme]] is a lexical unit and a [[morpheme]] is a morphological unit. (See [[emic unit]].)
More specifically, a grammeme is a value of a [[grammatical category]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Recent advances in computational linguistics | url = http://www.freepatentsonline.com/article/Informatica/233291025.html | accessdate = 2011-08-13}}</ref> For example, singular and plural are grammemes of the category of [[grammatical number|number]].
''Grammeme'', earlier spelt ''grameme'', was the original term used by [[Kenneth Pike|Pike]]'s school for what they went on to call the ''[[tagmeme]]''.<ref>Pike, K.L. (1958), "On tagmemes, née gramemes", ''International Journal of American Linguistics'' 24(4):273ff.</ref>
