Established by the [[University of Pittsburgh]] in 2009, the '''Nicholas Rescher Prize for [[Philosophical method|Systematic Philosophy]]''' is intended to counter present-day tendencies to narrow specialization by rewarding and showcasing the work of philosophers who have addressed the historical “big questions” of the field in ways that nevertheless command the respect of specialists. Awarded biennially the prize consists of a gold medal together with a sum of $25,000. The prize is named for [[Nicholas Rescher]], Distinguished University Professor of Philosophy, who has served on the university’s faculty for over 50 years. The recipients to date are: [[Ernest Sosa]] (2010), [[Alvin Plantinga]] (2012, joint award) and [[Jürgen Mittelstraß]] (2012, joint award), [[Hilary Putnam]] (2015), and [[Ruth Millikan]] (2017).<ref name=soul>{{cite web|first=Bryan|title=Rescher Prize for Contributions to Systematic Philosophy|url=http://www.soulphysics.org/2010/02/rescher-prize-for-contributions-to/|publisher=soulphysics.org|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=typepad>{{cite web|title=http://leiterreports.typepad.com/blog/2010/09/rutgerss-sosa-wins-inaugural-rescher-prize-from-university-of-pittsburgh.html|url=http://leiterreports.typepad.com/blog/2010/09/rutgerss-sosa-wins-inaugural-rescher-prize-from-university-of-pittsburgh.html|publisher=typepad.com|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=utm>{{cite web|title=Nicholas Rescher (1928—)|url=http://www.iep.utm.edu/rescher/|publisher=utm.edu|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=pitt>{{cite web|title=Dr. Nicholas Rescher|url=http://www.pitt.edu/~rescher/|publisher=pitt.edu|accessdate=22 September 2013}}</ref><ref>http://www.philosophy.pitt.edu/node/327</ref>
