[[File:Bandera FE JONS.svg|thumb|250px|The flag of FE-JONS (during Francoism, FET-JONS), with the yoke and the set of arrows. The colour black represents gunpowder and the red blood.]]
[[File:Coat of Arms of Spain (1945-1977).svg|thumb|250px|[[Armorial achievement]] of Spain during the [[Francoist State]], consisting of the traditional escutcheon (arms of Castile, León, Aragon, Navarre and Granada) and the [[Pillars of Hercules]] with the motto ''Plus Ultra'', together with Francoist symbols: the motto «Una Grande Libre», the [[Eagle (heraldry)#Eagle of Saint John|Eagle of St. John]], and the yoke and arrows of the [[Catholic Monarchs]] which were also adopted by the Falangists.]]

The '''symbols of Francoism''' were iconic references to identify the [[Francoist State]] in [[Spain]] between 1936 and 1975. 
They serve as visual illustrations for the ideology of [[Francoist Spain]].   
Uniforms were designed for men and women that combined elements of the earlier [[Falangist]] and [[Carlist]] uniforms. 
The state developed new flags and escutcheons based on the traditional heraldry of the [[Spanish Monarchy|monarchy]], but now associated with the state.
The emblem of five arrows joined by a yoke was also adopted from earlier times, but after 1945 the arrows always pointed upward. 
This emblem appeared on buildings, plaques and uniforms.

Many statues of [[Francisco Franco]] were installed in public places, in part to lend legitimacy to his state.
Some towns, streets and plazas were given new names derived from Franco and his entourage.
Franco caused many monuments to be erected, some of them substantial buildings.
The most imposing is the ''[[Valle de los Caídos]]'', the Valley of the Fallen, incorporating a huge basilica built into the side of a mountain. War memorials and plaques commemorating those who had died in the [[Spanish Civil War]] were installed in many towns and villages.

After Franco's death in 1975, followed by the return to democracy, many symbols of Francoism were destroyed or removed and places renamed.
A law of October 2007 mandated removal of all remaining symbols from public buildings, 
with some exceptions for works of particular religious or artistic significance.

==Background==
[[File:Belchite - Convento de San Rafael.JPG|thumb|Convento de San Rafael in [[Belchite]], destroyed in the Civil War, now a monument]]
[[File:Franco eisenhower 1959 madrid.jpg|thumb|[[Francisco Franco]] and [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] in Madrid in 1959]]
The [[Second Spanish Republic]] was established in April 1931 after King [[Alfonso XIII of Spain|Alfonso XIII]] had forced the dictator General [[Miguel Primo de Rivera]] to resign,
followed by nationwide municipal elections.  The king and the former dictator fled the country when the republic was declared.
The new government inherited a bankrupt state.{{sfn|Ascunce|2012|p=74}}  
In an atmosphere of political unrest, opinions polarized between the extreme right and extreme left, often degenerating into violence.{{sfn|Horn|1996|p=54-56}}
On the right, the traditionalist [[Carlist]] movement revived.{{sfn|Payne|2000|p=160}}
In 1933, the aristocratic [[José Antonio Primo de Rivera]], son of the former dictator, founded the far-right [[Falange]] movement, similar to the Italian [[Fascism|Fascists]].{{sfn|Payne|2000|p=69ff}}
In February 1934 the Falange merged with the ''[[Juntas de Ofensiva Nacional-Sindicalista]]'' (J.O.N.S), another right-wing group.{{sfn|Payne|2000|p=99}}
Left-wing trade unions staged industry-wide or citywide strikes, and in [[Catalonia]] Marxist and Anarchist groups competed for power.{{sfn|Horn|1996|p=54-56}} 
Landless laborers seized land, occupied estates and burned churches.{{sfn|Wells|2011|p=141}}{{sfn|Jelen|Wilcox|2002|p=79-80}}

At a time of political crisis, on 17 July 1936, General Francisco Franco led the Spanish colonial army from [[Morocco]] to attack the mainland, starting the [[Spanish Civil War]].
A bitter war of attrition, in which over 500,000 people died, dragged out until 1 April 1939, when the Nationalists led by Franco had acquired full control of the country.{{sfn|Sandler|2002|p=828}}
Franco was supported by the Falange and the Carlist ''Comunión Tradicionalista'', and united the two parties to forming the ''Falange Española Tradicionalista y de las JONS'', or ''FET y de las JONS'', whose official ideology was the Falangists' 27 puntos. 
The new party was a wide-ranging nationalist coalition, closely controlled by Franco.{{sfn|Preston|1996|p=261-266}}

Franco had received material support in the civil war from both [[Adolf Hitler]] and [[Benito Mussolini]], rulers of Germany and Italy, but when [[World War II]] broke out in September 1939, he cited the exhausted state of his country in maintaining a position of neutrality.{{sfn|Leitz|2000|p=118}}
In June 1940, Spain changed to a position of non-belligerency.
Despite pressure from [[Axis powers|Axis]] diplomats, that is as far as Franco would go.{{sfn|Leitz|2000|p=121ff}}
After the war ended in 1945, Franco remained dictator of Spain, at first isolated among the democracies of post-war Western Europe.
This isolation was gradually eroded by the pressures of the [[Cold War]], with Spain signing a security treaty with the United States in 1953.{{sfn|Ramet|Ingebritsen|2002|p=130}}
In the 1960s Spain experienced a boom from a growing tourism industry and from relaxation of trade barriers, 
modernizing economically and then culturally, which placed pressure on the state's highly conservative values.{{sfn|Sánchez|2007|p=19}}
However, Franco held onto power until his death in November 1975.
Soon after, a transition to democracy began.{{sfn|Greenberg|Katz|Wheatley|Oliviero|1993|p=292}}
A 1977 amnesty law was passed under which Franco's followers were given immunity for past abuses in return for supporting the transition.{{sfn|Tremlett|2007}}

==Uniforms==
[[File:JoseAntonioFEJONS.jpg|thumb|José Antonio Primo de Rivera in the Falange blue shirt]]
Photographs taken at the ceremony in October 1933 when the ''[[Falange Española de las JONS]]'' was founded do not show anyone wearing a uniform,
but a picture of a meeting of the ''Junta Política'' a year later shows some (but not all) members in the official uniform.  
This consisted of a dark blue shirt with epaulettes and long black trousers.  The left pocket of the shirt bore the emblem of the Falange.{{sfn|Ofer|2010|p=38}}
Women wore the blue shirt and a knee-length black skirt, with a leather belt bearing the Falange emblem on its buckle.{{sfn|Ofer|2010|p=39}} 
At a meeting in the [[Teatro Calderón (Valladolid)|Teatro Calderón]] in [[Valladolid]] in March 1934 the hall was filled with banners and insignia, and many attendees wore the blue shirts, visually displaying what [[José Antonio Primo de Rivera]] called the "spirit of service and of sacrifice, the ascetic and military concept of life."{{sfn|Parkins|2002|p=167}} 
Later, upper-class women might use Falangist insignia on their clothes as fashion accessories. 
When Carmen Primo de Rivera, sister of José Antonio, married in December 1938 she had the yoke and arrows embroidered on her wedding dress.{{sfn|Parkins|2002|p=179}} 
After José Antonio died, a black tie was added in his memory.{{sfn|Wright|2008|p=66}}

After the union with the Carlists, the original Falange uniform became important in identifying genuine Falangists.{{sfn|Ofer|2010|p=39}} 
The red beret had become the symbol of carlism by the 1860s.{{sfn|Macclancy|2000|p=32}}
The new party, commonly known as the [[Movimiento Nacional]], was given a uniform with the Falangist blue shirt, the red Carlist beret and military belts.{{efn|The belts were made in the tannery of Estella.{{sfn|Origen de la camisa azul}}}}  
The party symbol was the Falangist yoke and arrows.{{sfn|Kallis|2002|p=230}}
A portrait of Franco by [[Ignacio Zuloaga]] from 1940  shows him wearing the blue shirt, military boots and jodhpurs,
and the red beret of the requetés.{{efn|The term ''requeté'' for the Carlist militia refers to a famous regiment by that name that fought in the [[First Carlist War]].{{sfn|Macclancy|2000|p=278}}}}{{sfn|Jurkevich|1999|p=162}}{{sfn|Zuloaga|1940}}

==Heraldic devices, symbols and icons==

[[File:Coat of Arms of Spain (1939-1945)-Bureaucratic Variant.svg|thumb|Copy of the model of the coat of arms called the "abridged" version for Franco's Spain. Approved in 1938, it was a simplified version of the coat of arms to promote bureaucratic aims. It was used on stamps, lottery tickets, identity documents, and buildings. A popular name for it was "coat of arms of the Eagle".{{sfn|Esparza Leibar|2006|p=231-274}}]]

===Flag===

At the time of the Pronunciamiento of 17 and 18 July 1936, the insurgent military forces used the national flag with their coat-of arms superimposed, that is to say, the current "tricolor" with the 1869 coat of arms, which had been approved by the [[Spanish Constitution of 1931]]. However, in the operations, especially in the air and naval combats, the insurgents soon experienced confusion in distinguishing their units from those of the government. Also, within the insurgent heterogenic political families, the [[Carlism|Carlists]] in [[Navarre]] insisted on going into combat with flags that were red and gold or white embroidered with red, known as the burgundy of San Andrés, and they included a wide variety of emblems with a mixture of symbols of the monarchy and religion, the latter being particularly directed to the worship of the "Sacred Heart".{{sfn|Peña López|Alonso González|2004|p=17}}{{sfn|Esparza Leibar|2006|p=231-274}}

The government aimed to resolve this flag situation with the Decree of 29 August 1936, signed by General [[Miguel Cabanellas]], which reinstated the red and yellow flag. 
There was no reference to the dimensions nor the coat of arms, so the insurgent forces employed a host of distinctive coats of arms. 
To settle this situation, the Junta added an order to the Decree on 13 September 1936, signed by Colonel Federico Montaner. 
This defined the shapes and dimensions of the Army's flags to be the same as before the proclamation of the Republic.
The coat of  arms was that of the Republic. 
Eventually, considering the aims of the Falange, a new design for the coat of arms was formally specified and regulated by Decree number 470, 2 February 1938, signed by General Franco.{{sfn|Peña López|Alonso González|2004|p=17}}{{sfn|Esparza Leibar|2006|p=231-274}}

===Escutcheon===

The escutcheon, popularly known the  "Eagle escutcheon", and then representative of the insurgent group and its ideology,  was imposed after the conflict as the national escutcheon for [[Spain]]. It included some minor technical improvements which were approved in 1945, during the period of the Francoist State itself  and also during the period of democratic transition until 1981. Certain symbolic value changes were approved in 1977, such as making the eagle's wings much more open.{{sfn|Historia de la Bandera de España}}

By the express directive of the Franco government, the design of the shield for the national emblem represented a departure from the traditional one that had been used in its various forms since 1868. After this  change,  the escutcheon of [[Spain]] was attached to the State  and not the Monarchy.  Without affecting  the basic design, the shield was divided into four with the coats of arms of [[Castile and León|Castille]], [[Province of León|León]], [[Aragon]] and [[Navarre]], plus the «enté en point» of [[Granada]]. The inclusion of other historical heraldic elements gave a clear symbolic significance: "The set of arrows and the yoke of the Catholic Monarchs, whose adoption as a badge is one of the great successes of our Falange, must appear on the official arms to indicate what should be the tone of the New State."{{sfn|Luengo|2012|p=19}}

The Eagle on [[Francisco Franco|Franco]]'s escutcheon had already been used on the arms of the [[Catholic Monarchs]]. 
It was the [[Eagle (heraldry)#Eagle of Saint John|Eagle of Saint John the Evangelist]], which Queen [[Isabella I of Castile]] used on an evangelist escutcheon to which she added the words ''sub umbra alarum tuarum protege nos'' (protect us under the shadow of your wings).{{sfn|V Centenario Isabel I de Castilla}}
The heraldry  used by Franco  was similar to that of the  Catholic Monarchs, the arms of [[Aragon]]-[[Sicily]] replaced by those of the Navarre, the addition of the [[Pillars of Hercules]] and the motto One, Great and Free''.{{sfn|The coat of arms}}

=== Origin of the Yoke, arrows and Gordian knot ===
[[File:Losar emblemas 20071021.jpg|thumb|Emblems of the Catholic Monarchs on the facade of the Church of Santiago ([[Losar de la Vera]], Cáceres), c. 1500.]]

In Spanish heraldic tradition, the yoke, set of arrows and the [[Gordian Knot]],  were elements which were joined with the leaves and the pomegranate and the motto ''[[Tanto monta, monta tanto, Isabel como Fernando|Tanto monta, monta tanto]]'' (Equal opposites in balance), the personal motto and prenuptial agreement of the [[Catholic Monarchs]] [[Isabella I of Castile]] and [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]], as embodied  in the song of  Pedro Marcuello.{{sfn|Marcuello|1987}}{{sfn|Menéndez Pidal|2004|p=204}}
This motto was used upon the weapons of both Monarchs from 1475. 
They made an agreement, now called ''Concordia de Segovia'' and the coat of arms is a graphic representation of this pact which united the two most important Monarchs on the peninsula.  It is the oldest known image of the escutcheon.{{sfn|Menéndez Pidal|2004|p=211}}

The bundle of arrows may have its origins in the Roman ''fasces'', a bundle of rods and an axe with the blade projecting, that were carried before the magistrates to show their power.  The arrows pointed downward to show they were ready for use in executing criminals or for warfare.{{sfn|Cruz|Suzuki|2009|p=54}}
With the marriage of Ferdinand and Isabella, the bundle of arrows meant the union of Castile and Aragon to create Spain.  The yoke was Isabel's and the arrows Ferdinand's.
The F was the first letter of Fernando's name, and the Y the first letter of Isabella's.
The [[Gordian knot]], cut, united the two.{{sfn|Fernández|Porto|Celada|2004|p=73}} 
The number of arrows varied, but always pointed downwards. Over time, the badge of the Catholic Monarchs spread to other heraldic compositions, and was adopted in some of its variants as the emblems of not only towns and cities such [[Ronda]], [[Marbella]] and [[Málaga]], but also [[Puerto Rico]] and the  [[Netherlands]].{{sfn|Menéndez Pidal|2004|p=345}}

=== Emblem of the Falange ===

[[File:Yugo-y-flechas.jpg|thumb|Sign on public housing built during the Francoist State ( Madrid, 2007). The official single party used its association with the National Movement, and with it the FET-JONS, to try to carry out National Syndicalists measures, although these had little effect.]]
The adoption of this symbol was explained by a professor at the [[University of Granada]], [[Fernando de los Ríos]], who had socialist leanings. In  a class on political law  of the [[Fascism|Fascist]] state and its symbols, he made a drawing on the blackboard of a set of arrows linked with a yoke, indicating that this would be the symbol of Fascism and to have been born or raised in [[Spain]].  He said that if ever there was a Spanish fascism, this would be the emblem."''{{sfn|Cinco siglos de yugo y flechas}}
Juan Aparicio López,, a student attending the class, suggested adoption of this symbol for JONS of [[Onésimo Redondo]] and [[Ramiro Ledesma Ramos]] ([[Juntas de Ofensiva Nacional-Sindicalista]]). He also proposed the 'red and black' and the motto "Spain: one, great and free".{{sfn|Juan Aparicio López}}
The J.O.N.S adopted the [[yoke and arrows]] symbol, which immediately became popular due to its geometrical simplicity, warlike symbolism and invocation of a time when Spain was glorious.{{sfn|Ramos|1988|p=70}}
The symbol was adopted by the Falange at the time of the merger on 13 February 1934.{{sfn|Irasuegui|2010|p=117}}
The yoke and arrows represented the union of the five kingdoms of Castile, Leon, Aragon, Granada and Navarre, 
and both national unity and the glories of the period of Ferdinand and Isabella were persistent themes of Franco's Spain.{{sfn|Teichova|Matis|2003|p=125}}

The poet and activist [[Rafael Sánchez Mazas]] wrote, in an edition of the magazine ''El Fascio''1933 the reasons for the Spanish Falange's adoption  of some aspects of those used by  the Catholic Monarchs was because of their origin in the works of the Roman poet [[Virgil]] (70 BC – 19 BC). The symbolism of the arrows, as an expression of war was used in Virgil's ''[[Aeneid]]'', and the yoke, a symbol for agricultural, was based in Virgil's poem, the [[Georgics]], and was meant to provide a falangist symbolism:
''... We integrate  the yoke and the set of arrows into the escutcheon. If the yoke without the arrows is heavy, the arrows without the yoke are in danger of becoming too scattered. We are changing, rather than to a policy, to a discipline, to a behavior, to a style, to a way of being, to an education.''{{sfn|Haz y Yugo}}
Those responsible for the Falange ideology, such as José Antonio Primo de Rivera, Juan Aparicio, [[Ernesto Giménez Caballero]], [[Ramiro Ledesma]], Orbegozo, wrote in the journal ''Fascio'' that the chosen emblem was also close to Italian Fascism.{{sfn|El Fascio Index 1933}}

=== Víctor ===

[[File:Vítor (Symbol).svg|thumb|Detail of the"víctor". It contains each one of the letters in the word victor.]]
The "victor" is a symbol from the Ancient Roman Empire.
After the Edict of Milan in the year 313 AD, the ''crismón'' appeared on coins, flags and eventually also became part of the shields of the Roman legionaries. 
According to legend, the night before the battle of the [[Ponte Milvio]], the ''crismón''  with the words ''in hoc signo vinces'' (In this sign, you conquer') appeared to Emperor [[Constantine the Great]] in his dreams. The next day the Emperor replaced the Imperial eagle by the ''crismón'' on the standard, the ''[[labarum]]'', and he won the battle.
Over time, it was gradually included, in varying forms, on the Roman crowns. It had become the symbol of the victor and the victorious.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}
From the fourteenth century, it was adopted as the emblem for doctors by some Spanish universities, such as the [[University of Salamanca]] and later [[Alcalá de Henares]], and is in mural inscriptions done in red or black paint that remain there today. Finally, it was chosen as suitable for use in the ''Victory Parade''  (July 18, 1939) and, thereafter, throughout the Franco dictatorship, as emblem of Franco.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}
Mistakenly  it was thought it had been designed by Corintio Haza, who incorporated astrological symbols in the emblem to protect the ''Caudillo''.{{sfn|Constantino I}}

=== Guidon, head of State's standard and coat of arms of Franco ===
[[File:Coat of Arms of Francisco Franco as Head of the Spanish State.svg|thumb|The personal coat of arms of Franco.]]

The [[Colours, standards and guidons#Spain|guidon]], the personal military flag, and a [[Royal standard|head of State's standard]] were created in 1940 and then used until the death of the dictator. The stripe between the two dragons separates the two [[Pillars of Hercules]] which have silver columns, gold Corinthian capitals and are headed with crowns. The crown nearest to the stripe, which is always on the column placed on the lower part of the flag, is an [[Imperial crown]] with a central upright bar. The one on the other column is a Royal crown, this has a more open top and it is always on the column placed on the top half of the flag.{{sfn|Morales|Alegría|2001}}
The [[Royal Bend of Castile]], which was a personal badge of the Castilian Monarchs and later used by the [[House of Habsburg]], was used as the basis  for the creation of the escutcheon. 
The standard, the flag which was flown at official residences, barracks and on ships of the [[Spanish Navy]], was a square with the elements mentioned above.{{sfn|Morales|Alegría|2001}}
''La Banda de Castilla'' and the Columns of Hercules form part of the personal escuteon used by Franco as Chief of State. The coat of arms also contained the [[Laureate Cross of Saint Ferdinand]]  as [[supporter]] and  an open crown without [[Half-arch (crown)|arches]] known as the crown of military leadership.<ref>{{cite web |title=Super-libris of Franco, Francisco (1892-1975)|work=Ex-libris Database|editor= Royal Library (Madrid)|url=http://encuadernacion.realbiblioteca.es/index.php?p=searchexlibris&t=identificacion&i=80|accessdate=2013-05-06|language=Spanish}}</ref>

== Statues of Franco ==
[[File:Convent Sant Doménec Franco.jpg|thumb|Equestrian statue in Valencia]]
[[File:Francoayto.jpg|thumb|The last equestrian statue of Franco. Removed from the town centre of [[Santander, Cantabria|Santander]], 18 December 2008.]]
[[File:Las huellas de Franco, Ceuta (2).jpg|thumb|"Franco's Footprints", part of the monument to the Victoria Convoy, in Ceuta. The footprints were filled with concrete in February 2010.]]

The statues are varied sculptural representations of the dictator: busts, equestrian statues, etc., which the state placed in many Spanish cities. The purpose of having so many statues has changed over time.  It has been suggested that up to 1959 (and especially in the 1940s) the purpose of the many statues was to legitimize the state  and "perpetuate the memory of victory". It has been further suggested that in the 1960s  these were a special tribute  to show "appreciation of Franco and his achievements" (in a spirit of commemorating  the 25 Years of Peace). In the last period (after the death of Franco until 1978) the statues were to "secure the memory" of an "unchanging goal.{{sfn|Andrés|2006|pp=11-12}}

The most important equestrian statues were placed in prominent places in [[Valencia]], [[Santander, Cantabria|Santander]] and the ''Nuevos Ministerios''  in Madrid. The original was designed in 1959 by [[José Capuz Mamano]].{{sfn|Irigoyen de la Rasilla|2001|p=41}}
This statue is at the [[Complutense University]] in Madrid, with other copies in Barcelona,{{sfn|Ollés|2008}} Zaragoza (1948),{{sfn|Defensa ... Zaragoza}} Melilla,{{sfn|Retiran de Melilla la última estatua}} Ferrol,{{sfn|La última estatua ecuestre...}}{{sfn|IU quiere ver fundida...}} and the Institute of Maeztu Ramiro in Madrid (1942, a smaller one than the original and moved to the Infantry Academy in Toledo in the 1980s to the Infantry Academy in Toledo.{{sfn|La Academia de Infanteria}}

Places where statues can currently be found:
* [[Ferrol, Galicia|Ferrol]]: a statue of over six metres high, at Franco's birthplace. Originally placed in la Plaza de España, it is now in the Museo Naval de Herrerías, inside the military naval dockyard.
* [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]]: on the side of the main facade of the Infantry Academy in Toledo.
* [[Valencia]]: an equestrian statue of the dictator which was  withdrawn from Valencia in 1983 and is  now preserved in the courtyard of the convent of Santo Domingo.
* [[Melilla]]: retains the only statue of Franco that can be seen standing on a public road and, after being withdrawn in 2005 due to road works that were to take place, was placed back about 50 meters from its previous location. This statue was made before Franco became the Head of State and celebrates his achievements in the War of Africa.
* [[Tenerife]]: in the town of [[El Rosario, Tenerife|El Rosario]], there is plinth with Franco's bust, which records that in June 1936 the then commanding General of the Canary Islands (Franco) met there with officers of the garrison to prepare for the uprising.
* [[La Coruña]]: in various parts of the city, there are sculptures and plaques, with the image of the dictator on horseback surrounded by the Moorish guard of the Palace of Maria Pita.
* [[Oviedo]]: next to San Francisco Park and within the complex of buildings belonging to the Civil Government of [[Asturias]], a bronze statue of Franco on the side facing the park.

===Statues recently removed===

* Until February 2010, in [[Ceuta]] there was a monument called "Franco's feet," where his footprints were next to the only shrine in the city.{{sfn|Defensa retira Los pies de Franco}}
* The last statue of Franco in Santander was withdrawn on December 18, 2008.{{sfn|Salinas|2008}}
* A statue of Franco in the courtyard of the Military Academy of [[Zaragoza]] was withdrawn in August 2006.{{sfn|Gómez|2006}}
* A bust situated in Puebla de Vallbona, [[Valencia]] was removed in September 2005.
* In [[Guadalajara]], in March 2005, the decision was taken to remove the statue of General Franco from the Square Beladíez and the bust of José Antonio Primo de Rivera Park Concordia.{{sfn|El Ayuntamiento de Guadalajara... 2005}}
* On March 17, 2005 the statue was removed from the ''Nuevos Ministerios'' which was at the [[Paseo de la Castellana]] in [[Madrid]].{{sfn|Retiran la estatua ecuestre de Franco en Madrid}}
* On June 9, 2017 the stone bust was removed from the Plaza Mayor in [[Salamanca]]

== Monuments ==

===War memorials and Plaques to "Those Fallen for God and for Spain." ===

'''War memorials''' and '''plaques''' for those "Fallen for God and Spain" were placed in many villages, most on the outside of the churches. They contained a list of names of the dead people belonging to the Spanish Nationalist party followed by the declaration 'Present!' similar to that of José Antonio Primo de Rivera. The plaques, although there were many kinds, were usually made of marble and topped with bronze or other metal. Sometimes the plaques were placed on the walls of the church, or if there was a wall nearby, at the burial place of the victims named on the plaque. If there was a cross-shaped monument or low obelisk that recorded the names, a plaque was attached to it. Many places have now chosen to move this type of monument to the cemeteries, and in some cases they have been turned into tributes to the "fallen" from both sides.
There was another use of plaques, this was  at the opening of institutions and infrastructure such as railway lines, stations, reservoirs, etc., These plaques still exist today.
Many of the plaques and monuments are neither maintained nor withdrawn.

