=== The Victory Arch ===

[[File:Madrid - Moncloa - Arco de la Victoria - 20050220.jpg|thumb|Victory Arch ([[Madrid]]).]]
The Victory Arch of Madrid (''Arco de la Victoria de Madrid'') is situated in the [[Moncloa-Aravaca]] district of Madrid. 
The monument was built between 1953 and 1956 by order of Franco to commemorate his victory in the [[Spanish Civil War]].{{sfn|Baskett|2003|p=133}} 
The {{convert|40|m}} high arch commemorates the nationalist victory in the [[Battle of Ciudad Universitaria]], in which the [[University City of Madrid|University City]] was destroyed. Inscriptions in Latin describe the victory and the construction of the new University City.{{sfn|Victory arch}}
Behind it is the monument to the Fallen from Madrid, designed in 1949 by the architect [[Manuel Herrero de Palacios]], a monumental circular building roofed with a cupola.
Today it is the home of the municipal council of the Moncloa - Aravaca district.{{sfn|Álvarez-Fernández|2007|p=61}}

=== Monument to the Fallen in Pamplona ===

[[File:Caídosfront.JPG|thumb|Monument to the Fallen in [[Pamplona]] ([[Spain]]).]]

Popularly known as the Monument to the Fallen, the real name is ''Navarra a sus Muertos en la Cruzada'' (Navarre to its Dead in the Crusade), as indicated on its facade.
The building was erected in memory of the dead from Navarre, a Nationalist stronghold during the Civil War, and is located in the heart of the city of [[Pamplona]], the capital of [[Navarre]]. The building was designed by the architects Victor Eusa and José Yamoz.
The names of the 5,000 people of Navarre who died in combat in the civil war were inscribed on its walls,
but today they are covered by a sheet.{{sfn|Corpas Mauleón|2012|p=54}}
Today the building is known as the ''Sala de Exposiciones Conde Rodezno'' (Conde Rodezno Exhibition Hall) and is used for small municipal exhibitions.{{sfn|Sala de Exposiciones Municipal Conde Rodezno}}

=== Headquarters, Cuartel de La Montaña ===
[[File:Parque de la Montaña.JPG|thumb|Commemorative plaque.]]

The Cuartel de la Montaña was a military building in Madrid that achieved notoriety as the place where the military uprising of July 1936 began in the city.
On July 19, 1936 in Madrid, General Fanjul, without a commission, but charged with the uprising of the city, came in civilian clothes, to  the headquarters, Cuartel de La Montaña. Instead of going out with troops to take the vital points of the capital, he simply proclaimed the state of war and became powerful with 1,500 men (of whom there were about 140 officers) and approximately 180 Falangists from the Cuartel de La Montaña.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}

That afternoon, the base was surrounded by poorly armed troops loyal to the government of the Republic Assault Guards, civilians and militia. At dawn on 20 July, shelling of the barracks began. The rebels resisted for only a few hours. Differences of opinion amongst themselves,  led some rebels to fly the white flag while others were firing on the attackers. The garrison fell, being almost completely destroyed. The entry of the attacking forces resulted in the murder of most of the officers (ninety of one hundred forty) and the Falangists. There were between 150 and 300 dead.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}

The building, which had been mostly destroyed during the siege, during the war suffered the impact of numerous artillery attacks because of its proximity to the front line, which to all intents and purposes stayed in the same place since early 1937. Towards the end of the war it was just a set of ruins, some of which could still be seen in the early sixties.
The park, Parque del Cuartel de la Montaña,  was inaugurated on 20 July 1972, when Franco was still in power and [[Carlos Arias Navarro]], the future prime minister, was mayor of Madrid. It incorporates  a monument, also from 1972, by Joaquín Vaquero Turcios in memory of those who died in its defence. This consists of a bronze figure representing the body of an injured man at the centre of a wall sculpted in the form of sandbags.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}

=== The ruins of Belchite ===

[[File:Belchite - Vista general01.JPG|thumb|The Ruins of Belchite.]]
The Battle of Belchite occurred during the Republican offensive in Aragon that started in August 1937, with Zaragoza as the target.  For various reasons, including heat, lack of water and the military superiority of the Nationalists, the offensive was unsuccessful.  Starting on 1 September 1937, the republicans concentrated on Belchite, with an intense artillery bombardment combined with aerial bombing.  The town was totally ruined and 6,000 people had died when the defenders surrendered on 6 September 1937.  Although the outcome was a Republican victory, the delay caused by the battle gave the Nationalists time to regroup and prevent the advance to Zaragoza.{{sfn|Ryan|2012|p=102}}

Franco decreed that the original town be left in its state of ruin as a monument.{{sfn|Ward|2004|p=202}}
Republican prisoners were made to build a new town of Belchite, but the original town has not been rebuilt.
The ruins remain as a monument that attracts small numbers of battlefield tourists each year.{{sfn|Ryan|2012|p=106}}

=== Monuments for the Battle of Ebro ===
[[File:Poble Vell (Corbera d'Ebre) 1.jpg|thumb|Ruin of Corbera de Ebro.]]

The bloodiest battle of the Civil War was fought on the left bank of the river [[Ebro]].

* In memory of General Franco's victory, the town of [[Corbera de Ebro]] was left just as it had been after the battle.
* At an elevation of 427 metres at [[Quatre Camins]] a stone cross stands in memory of the Third Requetes of Our Lady of Montserrat, the Carlist Nationalist unit formed by Catalan volunteers, which suffered heavy casualties in this place. St. Andrew's Cross of red stands on the pedestal.
* At elevation 481 in [[Punta Targa]], a monument stands for the brotherhood of the Third Requetes of Our Lady of Montserrat. The base of the monument is an [[ossuary]] containing the remains of combatants from both sides.
* At the crossroads for Faterella and [[Villalba de los Alcores]] there  is a monolith erected in memory of the soldiers of the 4th Division of Navarre who died in on the banks of the Ebro.
* At [[Coll del Moro]], on the outskirts of [[Gandesa]], a monolith from 1953 marks the position from which Franco personally led the final attack. The monument has been vandalized with graffiti both for and against Franco's Spain.
* On one of the peaks of [[Puig de l'Àliga]] near [[Gandesa]], there is another monument but the original inscription has been lost over time.
* In [[Prat de Compte]] in front of the school there is a cross in memory of the 'Fallen for God and for Spain'.

=== Monument for the Massacre of Paracuellos ===
[[File:20070519 - Vista del cementerio de Paracuellos.jpg|thumb|View of the [[Paracuellos de Jarama|Paracuellos]] Cemetery. In the background is the white cross drawn on the hill where the killings took place.]] 
Republican Militia guards killed over a thousand prisoners in the "[[Paracuellos massacres|Massacre of Paracuellos]]", during the [[Battle of Madrid]], in the area around San Jose, in the municipality of [[Paracuellos de Jarama]], and Soto Aldovea, within the boundary of [[Torrejón de Ardoz]].  They are commemorated by a large white cross on the slopes of the Cerro de San Miguel, near the river [[Jarama]] and visible from the airport of Madrid-Barajas.{{sfn|Plano del Camposanto de Paracuellos}}

=== The Fortress at Toledo ===
{{main|Alcázar of Toledo}}
[[File:Alcazar de Toledo.jpg|thumb|'''El Alcázar''', Toledo, a fortress built out of rock, is  located in the upper part of the city of [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] and  it overlooks the city.]]

In the third century the Alcázar of Toledo was a Roman palace. It was restored during the reigns of Alfonso VI and Alfonso X and modified in 1535.
During the Civil War it was used by Colonel [[José Moscardó Ituarte]] as a defence building and a place of resistance. During a siege there, which lasted 70 days, from 22 July to 28 September 28, 1936, it was completely destroyed by troops loyal to the [[Second Spanish Republic]]. 
Later it was rebuilt.
Since 1998 it has housed the Library of [[Castile-La Mancha]], and from 2010 it has also held the Army Museum.
The siege and liberation were used by Francisco Franco to establish his dominance with his followers.
The newspaper ''Ultra'' named the building ''El Alcázar'' of Spain, although at first was a daily that referred to it as an historical landmark.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}

=== Monument to the cruiser "Baleares" ===

The Monument to the cruiser "Baleares" (''El Monumento al Crucero «Baleares»'') is located in the San Feixina Park, [[Palma, Majorca]].
It is controversial, with some groups calling for its removal.{{sfn|Oliver|2009}}
The monument was erected in memory of the crew of the [[Spanish cruiser Baleares]], which was torpedoed and sunk by destroyers of the [[Spanish Republican Navy]] in the [[Battle of Cape Palos]].  The monument was designed by the architects Don Francisco and Don José Roca Simó (father and son) and the sculptor José Ortells Cabanellas. It was inaugurated on 16 May 1947.  The column is {{convert|22|m}} high, topped by a huge cross.  At one time it also had a sculpture of a sailor clinging to an anchor.{{sfn|Fullana|ConolloyCota|2000}}

== Religious monuments ==

Franco was raised as a devout Catholic, and came to believe that Spanish nationalism and Catholic belief could not be separated.  He felt that Spain had a special religious mission, and completely identified his cause with the cause of the church.{{sfn|Payne|2011|p=199}}
Franco called his fight against the Republicans a "crusade" and presented his 1939 victory as a victory of [[Christian civilization]].{{sfn|Conway|Romijn|2008|p=150}}
When attending churches, he entered solemnly under a religious canopy.{{sfn|Soler|2005}}
On 15 April 1938, [[Vinaròs]] beach was captured, splitting the Republican-held area into two.
The head of the Navarre IV Division dipped his fingers in the water and made the sign of the cross, symbolically taking possession.{{sfn|Cardona|2012}}

St Teresa was designated by traditionalists and the Catholic Church as the "saint of the Spanish race". The Nationalist forces found a relic of the saint in Málaga, one of her hands, which was sent to Franco. He made a personal cult of devotion to the saint, keeping the relic in his home until he died.{{sfn|Pérez-Romero|1996|p=68}}

=== The Valley of the Fallen ===
[[File:SPA-2014-San Lorenzo de El Escorial-Valley of the Fallen (Valle de los Caídos).jpg|thumb|The Valley of the Fallen.]]
{{Main|Valle de los Caídos}}
This monument to the fallen in the civil war was built by Republican prisoners of war.
It is on a huge scale, with the basilica built into the side of a pine-covered mountain, 
with an enormous stone cross above the entrance.{{sfn|Simonis|2007|p=168-169}}   
The stone cross is {{convert|500|ft}} high and is visible from a distance of {{convert|30|mi}}.{{sfn|Encarnación|p=1}}
The monument and basilica were built in accordance with the Decree of 1 April 1940 providing for construction of a Basilica, monastery and youth headquarters, in a farm located on the slopes of the Sierra de Guadarrama (El Escorial), "to perpetuate the memory of the fallen of our glorious Crusade".{{sfn|Los comienzos del Valle de los Caidos}}
Construction began in the 1940s and the structure was completed in 1959.{{sfn|Encarnación|p=1}}

Franco's grave is beside the altar.
The monument is still visited by the dwindling group of his die-hard supporters on the anniversary of Franco's death.{{sfn|Simonis|2007|p=168-169}} 
José Antonio Primo de Rivera and many other combatants from both sides in the Spanish Civil War are buried in the valley.{{sfn|Olmeda|2010}}
Perhaps 50,000 of Franco's supporters are buried there, along with a handful of Republicans.{{sfn|Encarnación|p=1}}
Human rights groups have called for ''El Valle de los Caidos'' to be converted into a center that would teach visitors about the civil war and the Francoist State.
Others have asked that the bodies of Jose Antonio and Franco be removed, 
and that plaques or other methods be used to give visitors some understanding of the historical background.{{sfn|Encarnación|p=147}}

=== Sacred Heart of Jesus ===
[[File:Cerro-angeles1.jpg|thumb|Monument, the Sacred Heart of Jesus in [[Cerro de los Ángeles]], [[Getafe]], Spain.]]
{{Main|Cerro de los Ángeles}}
The ''Cerro de los Ángeles'' (Hill of the Angels) is the site of the ''Monumento al Sagrado Corazón'' (Monument of the Sacred Heart).
The original monument was created by the architect Carlos Maura Nadal and the sculptor  Aniceto Marinas y García, and was inaugurated by King Alfonso XIII on 30 May 1919.
It was destroyed on 7 August 1936 during the civil war.{{sfn|Monumento Antiguo}}
The Republicans dynamited the monument due to its religious and political symbolism.  
There was a proposal to replace it with a figure representing Liberty or the Republic, but this was not executed.{{sfn|González Martínez|1999|p=182}}

The current monument is similar in design to the 1919 monument, but on a larger scale.  
Construction began in 1944 to designs by the architects Pedro Muguruza and Luis Quijada Martínez.
The monument shows Christ with open arms, inviting all men to come to Him.  
The {{convert|11.5|m}} high statue on a {{convert|26|m}} pedestal is the work of Aniceto Marinas, and the group of sculptures around the base is by Fernando Cruz Solís.
The monument was opened in 1965.  The crypt, which did not exist in the original monument, was opened in 1975.{{sfn|El Monumento al Sagrado Corazón}}

== Place names ==
[[File:Alberche del Caudillo.jpg|thumb|Alberche del Caudillo, now [[Calera y Chozas]] in the [[Province of Toledo]]]]

===Towns and villages===
{{see also|Instituto Nacional de Colonización}}
Today, there are a dozen towns that preserve the memory of Franco in their official names. The only one which has the status of a municipality is [[Llanos del Caudillo]], with  726 inhabitants. Many other towns and cities that had similar names for decades, such as [[Ferrol, Galicia|El Ferrol del Caudillo]] (until 1982, in the province of La Coruña), or [[Barbate|Barbate de Franco]] (until 1998, in the province of [[Cadiz]]), withdrew the reference to Franco after the restoration of democracy. Franco wanted to honour generals from the Nationalist side by putting their names to various locations, and they still retain these. Such is the case of [[San Leonardo de Yagüe]], where [[Juan Yagüe|General Juan Yagüe]] was born, or [[Alcocero de Mola]], where [[Emilio Mola|General Emilio Mola]] died in a plane crash during the war.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}
The case of [[Numancia de la Sagra]] ([[Province of Toledo|Toledo]]) is an example. Since the [[Middle Ages]] this town was known as ''Azaña'', but during the [[Spanish Civil War|Civil War]] this coincided with the first name of the then Spanish Prime Minister, [[Manuel Azaña]], so it was replaced in 1936. The original name, Azana means ''wheel'' (Arab-Moorish word). The town is now called "Numancia", after the regiment  which captured it and "Sagra" for the region it belongs to.{{sfn|Villena Garcia|2010|p=277}}

=== Street names ===
[[File:Plaque generalisimo.jpg|thumb|Nameplate for la Avenida del Generalísimo.]]

The memory of Franco is still present in the names of the streets, squares and avenues of various towns and cities. There are also streets, avenues and squares in many cities and towns in Spain with names of generals from during the Civil War and the Nationalist party, military commanders such as [[Emilio Mola|Mola]], [[José Sanjurjo|Sanjurjo]], [[José Moscardó Ituarte|Moscardó]], [[Juan Yagüe|Yagüe]] and [[José Millán Astray|Millán Astray]]. Other names from the Franco time were used, such as José Antonio Primo de Rivera, [[Ramiro Ledesma Ramos|Ramiro Ledesma]], [[Onésimo Redondo]], [[José Calvo Sotelo]], etc.. Those that did not have a personal relationship with Franco, were those who had died before or during the war; José Antonio Primo de Rivera, who was imprisoned, opposed the National Uprising and become part of the earlier conspiracy.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}

==Removal of symbols==

In January 1980 the Madrid city council decided to rename twenty downtown streets, returning them to the names they had before 14 April 1931, when the Second Republic was created.  The Avenida del Generalísimo, which had been created since that date, became the [[Paseo de la Castellana]].{{sfn|Lafuente|1980}}
In 1981 the Avenida de José Antonio in Madrid was renamed ''La Gran Vía''.{{sfn|La Gran Vía, Madrid}}
But despite the withdrawal of some of the symbols during the first years of the Transition, some symbols remained more than thirty years after his death.

The Spanish [[Historical Memory Law]], approved by the [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Congress of Deputies]] on 31 October 2007, mandated the removal of commemorative plaques, statues and other symbols from public buildings.  It also opened the public archives covering the period and facilitated the task of locating and exhuming the graves of victims.{{sfn|Tremlett|2007}}
Under the 2007 law introduced by the socialist government of [[José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero]], Falangist symbols had to be removed from public view, and streets and plazas that honored Franco and his entourage had to be renamed.{{sfn|Govan|2010}}
The law was criticized by both left-wing and right-wing observers, for being too lenient or too severe.
A historian said that by focusing on the abuses committed by Franco the government was presenting the left-wing republican government in too favorable a light, ignoring the many problems of the feuding [[socialism|socialist]], [[anarchism|anarchist]], [[communism|communist]] and separatist groups.{{sfn|Kingstone|2007}}

In 2010 the department of National Heritage stopped offering tours of Franco's private quarters in the [[Royal Palace of El Pardo]], although tours of the older parts of the palace with "high artistic value" would continue.
In December 2010 the ''Valle de los Caidos'' was reopened, but with tight security systems to prevent vandalism or destruction by militant members of victims' associations.{{sfn|Govan|2010}}
As of 2011 the government was considering exhuming Franco's body from the ''Valle de los Caidos'' and reburying it beside his wife in a municipal cemetery.  There were some protests, but many supported the plan to transform the site into a place of reconciliation, with plaques to explain the past. [[Ramón Jáuregui]], the responsible minister, said, "We have dealt with the past little by little.  Maybe we're tackling this site a little late, but prudence has been the key to our peaceful transition."{{sfn|Rainsford|2011}}

There was much debate regarding symbols that might affect the Church, so an exception was introduced for religious reasons, and an exception made for monuments with particular artistic value. There are some emblematic symbols such as the yoke and arrows on the Casa Sindical (a brick tower facing the [[Museo del Prado]]) and the Central Headquarters of the [[Movimiento Nacional|Movimiento]], the Alcalá de Madrid which was built in a [[rationalist]] style.

